SIMPLE: electrify
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Electrify
<hw>E*lec"tri*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Electrified</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Electrifying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph>
<ety>[<ets>Electr</ets>ic + <ets>-fy</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
communicate electricity to; to charge with electricity; <as>as, to
<ex>electrify</ex> a jar</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause electricity to pass through; to affect by
electricity; to give an electric shock to; <as>as, to <ex>electrify</ex>
a limb, or the body</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To excite suddenly and violently, esp. by something
highly delightful or inspiriting; to thrill; <as>as, this patriotic
sentiment <ex>electrified</ex> the audience</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If the sovereign were now to immure a subject in defiance of the
writ of habeas corpus . . . the whole nation would be instantly
<qex>electrified</qex> by the news.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Try whether she could <qex>electrify</qex> Mr. Grandcourt by
mentioning it to him at table.</q> <rj><qau>G. Eliot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To equip for employment of electric power; to modify
(a device) so that it uses electrical power as the main source of
energy; <as>as, to <ex>electrify</ex> a railroad</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Electrify</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Electrify
<hw>E*lec"tri*fy</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become
electric.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Electrine</ent>⟦br⟧
